<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN TESTS HYDROGEN-POWERED MINI-TRAIN
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  April 12 (CNA) 04/13/07  10:42:28
</P>
<P>
The National Science and Technology Museum in Kaohsiung County in
southern Taiwan has successfully tested a mini-train using power
generated by a hydrogen fuel-cell, according to a Radio Taiwan
International report released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The train, the first of its kind in the world, is part of the
museum's efforts to promote environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The mini-train is not only environmentally friendly, it is also
safe, makes little noise, and need not be re-charged often.
</P>
<P>
Lee Yuan-tze,  a co-winner  of the 1986 Nobel  Prize  in
chemistry who retired from the presidency of Academia Sinica,
took a test ride on Wednesday. He said that with a decrease in
available energy resources, it is important for scientists to
develop renewable energy.
</P>
